<font color="#FF0000">ANSWER TO ANGELA</font><br>
<tt>Thu Feb 19 16:43:48 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Dear Angela,<br><br>
   At your college, you may have heard some things that are not really accurate about the war.  I say this because you stated that your father accepted his draft notice because he believed &quot;my country right or wrong.&quot;  At the time the Vietnam War began, we were at a period of the Cold War during which everything seemed to be going in favor of the communists.  Since the end of World War II, communist governments had been steadily taking over country after country.  One of the most threatening events was the introduction of missiles with nuclear warheads to Cuba, which had just been taken over by a new communist insurgent group.  We had nuclear warheads pointed at us from just 90 miles south of Florida.<br>
   At the time, over 100 new contries were being formed from former European colonies.  Nearly all of them became independent without bloodshed.  A few were the scenes of civil wars.  However, there was no other former colony gaining independence at this time that was the scene of so much bloodshed as Vietnam.  The reason for this was that nearly 100% of the Vietnamese wanted to be independent from the French, but only about 15% of these were communists who wanted to install a communist government by force (estimate by Bernard Fall).  The other 85% were divided.  The Cao Dai, Hoa Hao, and some Buddhist sects wished to create some form of theocracy.  The Christians sought to model their government on western democracies.  Many peasants just wanted to be left alone.  However, the 15% were united to propagate communism and armed better, having received guns first from the United States and then from communist China. They were able to take over the northern half of the country.  Many Vietnamese fled to the South after that, and later, there was a peasant rebellion against the communists. After the rebellion was crushed, the communists turned their attention to the South.  By that time, their pro-Chinese leaders had been replaced by pro-Soviet ones.  There was bitter opposition to them in the South, especially from those refugee groups that had fled after the communists took over the North.  In spite of some false reports, these people were not pro-French and some of them had also fought for independence against the French forces.  The staunchly pro-French Vietnamese had been allowed to emigrate to France after the war and were no longer there.  There was also a minority of pro-communist Viet Cong, many of whom had been trained in the North.<br>
   Not liking totalitarian governments and because I thought that our system permits people more freedom, I was glad to have the chance to serve my country in the Vietnam War.  I have never been disturbed by any of the movies, which I generally rate according to how realistic they seem. Unfortunately, I am frequently filled with anger and disgust by actual situations and events that continue to occur.  I have been referred to as a political exile from the United States because employment discrimination against veterans in there has forced me to live outside the country for most of the 30 years since I received by honorable discharge.  The same kind of discrimination has forced hundreds of thousands of veterans to sleep on the streets of American cities or in shelters for the homeless.  Because I frequently have to cross borders, I often have to show my American passport.  When I did this, I often felt deep shame, not because we fought or lost the war but for many other reasons, including the following:<br><br>
1. Hundreds of thousands of Vietnamese who fled their country after the communists took over received no help whatsoever from the United States and rotted for decades in camps set up in countries too poor themselves to take care of them.  American freighters and even U. S. Navy ships ignored centuries of tradition insisting that the shipwrecked be helped and passed by ships full of refugees that were sinking or being plundered by pirates.  I personally know some of the survivers from these ships that were helped by the Kap Anamur, a German ship that was allowed to pick up a limited number of these shipwrecked refugees and give them asylum in Germany.  To leave on the floating wrecks on which they were trying to escape the communist hell, the refugees had to pay one kilogram of gold each to the communist authorities.  (Remember the myth that the South Vietnamese were corrupt but the communists were not.)  Some families scraped together everything they had to put just one of their children on such a ship in the hopes that he or she would survive and be able to live in a free country.  Many of these refugees perished at sea.  Some of the young girls were taken as slaves by pirates.  Others arrived in Hong Kong to be placed in concentration camps so horrible that they would act to deter other Vietnamese from coming there.  Later, many were forceably deported back to Vietnam.  Some committed suicide to avoid deportation.  Over 58,000 young Americans died for the goal of &quot;winning the hearts and minds of the Vietnamese people,&quot; a slogan used for our civil action operations. After we did, we let those who believed in freedom perish because it did not pass in the concepts of the protestor politicians, who were preaching that the Vietnamese wanted us out so that they could enjoy the wonderful socialist system being introduced from the North.<br><br>
2. After the Second World War and especially during the 1960s (before AIDS), Americans adopted a very liberal attitude toward sex.  As a result, large numbers of children were born to Vietnamese women whose American fathers deserted them when they returned to the United States.  The children have claim to American citizenship and are treated with exteme contempt by the communists.  Only after years of protest were decent Americans able to move the government to accept these American citizens into the country.  However, they were first subjected to months or years of demeaning treatment in concentration camps in the Philippines for &quot;processing&quot;.  There are still many of them in Vietnam who wish to come to the United States, but the press has lost interest in them, so the government finds no need to take any action.  On German television, several of these people were interviewed.  One was a black man nearly reaching middle age, obviously the son of an American father.  He was in tears describing what he had to go through in Vietnam because of his background and skin color.  The United States, the richest and most sparcely populated country in the world, could easily take these few thousand refugees with a legal claim to American citizenship in.  The Vietnamese already accepted in America do not take away jobs, the create them for others with their diligence.  However, they speak negatively about the present Vietnamese government, and that would not pass into the concept of the happy socialist society that many American businessmen are trying to close deals with.<br><br>
3. There is a smug dismissal of the 200,000 to 300,000 American war veterans who have no home to live in as substance abusers or people with no skills.  Recently, however, I heard that studies showed that the more education a veteran had received, the more likely he is to become homeless.  I know from my own experience that veterans are systematically discriminated against in employment in the United States, making it more likely for less educated veterans to find jobs with salaries at or near the poverty level, while veterans with better skills are not likely to find any job at all.  The reason is that there was nearly full employment during the Vietnam War, ensuring a good, permanent job to anyone who could beat the draft system.  When the veterans returned, jobs were scarce, and the protestors holding the the jobs refused to accept veterans as subordinates or co-workers because they would feel uncomfortable working with them.  The government set up many agencies that were supposed to help veterans find work. The personnel in these agencies, mainly within the Department of Labor, looked after their own salaries and benefits and did nothing at all to help the veterans.  They were able to get away with this because veterans are the only group with affirmative action rights who may not sue an employer if they are discriminated against.<br><br>
4. Many of the most influential people in the American media and the universities are interested in peddling their own version of the war as &quot;fact&quot; and suppress any information that conflicts with their own prejudices.  The version being peddled paints the veterans either as war criminals or stupid suckers.  How many television shows have you seen in which the villain is a crazed Vietnam vet?  How many others have you seen where the veteran is a drunken bum being helped by some do-gooder?  The problems of these vets are always blamed on war experiences, not on the treatment they received after returning home, which for many vets is the real problem.<br><br>
   Bombarded by the kind of propaganda spread around in America, it is easy for me to understand why veterans dispair.  After all, if the war had been won, South Vietnam today would be one of the Asian tigers, like Thailand or South Korea.  Instead it is one of the poorest and most corrupt countries in the world with enormous numbers of political prisoners languishing in the labor camps.  Many of them have been there for decades because they were our allies.  Businessmen are now investing heavily in Vietnam because the communists are able to supply what they want: slave labor.  The state dictates how much factory workers may earn, and it is very little.  Labor unions are state-run and simply tell the workers to work harder for less pay because the state needs foreign capital.  A Vietnam vet, like the Korean War veterans, might have been able to accept the horrors he personally experienced as being necessary to preserve the freedom of the South Vietnamese and thereby protecting the independence of the entire free world if we had succeeded in keeping the communists out of at least part of Vietnam, Laos, and Cambodia. Instead, however, he has to look back at the misery with the realization that it was all for nothing. America did not have the guts to stick it out, and having lost, it did nothing to help our former allies who were suffering at the hands of the ruthless victors.  On top of that, their sacrifices were being made a joke of by those who considered themselves too good or too smart to serve in the armed forces.<br>
   Many veterans are overcome emotionally by their experiences and cannot think their situation through.  However, if you think about the war and its aftermath, perhaps you can understand why veterans like your father might have bad dreams and why so many feel deeply embittered.<br><br>

